[{"id":"VR797912","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two concentric rings of radii uppercase R and 2 uppercase R. Point P is on a line that passes through the common center of the rings and is perpendicular to the plane of the rings. The inner ring initially has charge negative uppercase Q and the outer ring initially has charge positive uppercase Q.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR797912.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two charged rings are concentric and have radii <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase R\"><math alttext=\"uppercase R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 uppercase R\"><math alttext=\"2 uppercase R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, as shown in the figure. Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> is located on a line that passes through the common center of the rings and is perpendicular to the plane of the rings. Each ring is uniformly charged, initially with charges <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive uppercase Q\"><math alttext=\"positive uppercase Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative uppercase Q\"><math alttext=\"negative uppercase Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>-</mo><mi>Q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> on the ring of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 uppercase R\"><math alttext=\"2 uppercase R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></math></span></span> and the ring of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase R\"><math alttext=\"uppercase R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, respectively. If each ring is given the opposite charge from what it had initially, what happens to the electric field magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E\"><math alttext=\"E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>E</mi></math></span></span> at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>? What evidence or reasoning supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR797912_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E\"><math alttext=\"E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>E</mi></math></span></span> stays the same. The integrals that express the electric field contributions of the rings change in sign but not magnitude.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E\"><math alttext=\"E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>E</mi></math></span></span> stays the same. The net charge of the two-ring system does not change.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E\"><math alttext=\"E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>E</mi></math></span></span> changes. The contribution to the electric field at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span> from the larger ring is greater in magnitude than the contribution from the smaller ring.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E\"><math alttext=\"E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>E</mi></math></span></span> changes. The contribution to the electric field at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span> from the smaller ring is greater in magnitude than the contribution from the larger ring.</p>"],"answer":0}]